  "prompt": "Why do I feel sleepy and tired after consuming non-drowsy cold/flu-relief medication?",
  "response": "There could be several reasons why you feel sleepy after taking \"non-drowsy\" cold and flu medication:\n\n1. Individual sensitivity\n- People can react differently to medications\n- Some individuals may be more sensitive to certain ingredients\n\n2. Medication ingredients\n- Some \"non-drowsy\" medications still contain antihistamines that can cause drowsiness\n- Ingredients like pseudoephedrine can cause fatigue as a side effect\n- Combination medications might have sedating components\n\n3. Underlying illness\n- Your body's immune response to fighting an infection can naturally make you feel tired\n- The illness itself can contribute to fatigue\n\n4. Dehydration\n- Cold/flu medications can cause dehydration\n- Dehydration can lead to feelings of tiredness\n\n5. Medication interactions\n- Other medications or supplements might interact and increase drowsiness\n- Caffeine or alcohol can affect how you process the medication\n\n6. Possible mislabeling\n- Some medications might not be as \"non-drowsy\" as claimed\n- Regulatory standards can vary\n\nIf persistent drowsiness is concerning, consult your healthcare provider or pharmacist. They can recommend alternatives or help you understand your specific reaction to the medication.",
